    <section class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed space-y-6">
      <p>If you have ever ordered carton boxes in Malaysia and been confronted with terms like "B flute single wall" or "BC double wall," you are not alone. Most business owners simply ask for "standard boxes" and hope for the best. But understanding flute types — the corrugated wave patterns inside cardboard — allows you to make smarter, more cost-effective packaging decisions. The right flute means better protection without overpaying.</p>

      <p>Quinocycle Sdn. Bhd. in Balakong, Selangor has been supplying corrugated carton boxes to Malaysian businesses since 2010. Here is our plain-English guide to flute types and how to choose the right one.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">What is a Flute in Corrugated Cardboard?</h2>
      <p>A corrugated carton box is made from flat liner sheets and a wavy middle layer called the fluting or medium. The wavy structure gives the board its strength — the arch shape of each wave transfers force efficiently, similar to an arch bridge. The size and frequency of these waves determines the flute type, which in turn determines thickness, cushioning ability, compressive strength, and cost.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Flute Type Reference Guide</h2>

      <div class="bg-surface-variant/50 border border-outline-variant/20 rounded-2xl p-6 my-8">
